{"title_page": "Qila Mubarak, Patiala", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Qila Mubarak|Qila Mubarak in Bathinda]]}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name = Qila Mubarak\n| native_name = \n| native_language = \n| image = Qila Mubarak, Patiala.jpg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Royal palace]]\n| locmapin = \n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| location = [[Patiala]], [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| area = \n| built = \n| architect = \n| architecture = \n| governing_body = \n| owner = \n| designation1 = \n| designation1_offname = \n| designation1_date = \n| designation1_number = \n| designation2 = \n| designation2_offname = \n| designation2_date = \n| designation2_number = \n| designation3 = \n| designation3_offname = \n| designation3_date = \n| designation3_number = \n| designation4 = \n| designation4_offname = \n| designation4_date = \n| designation4_number = \n| designation5 = \n| designation5_offname = \n| designation5_date = \n| designation5_number = \n}}\n\n'''Qila Mubarak''' ({{Lang-pa|'''\u0a15\u0a3c\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a2e\u0a41\u0a2c\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a15'''}}) is an ancient fortress of [[Sikh architecture]] in [[Patiala]], [[India]].<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/36639/ 4 heritage sites find saviour in Monument Fund]</ref> \n\n==History==\nQuila Mubarak was first built as a 'Kachigarhi' (Mud fortress) by [[Sidhu]] [[Jat]] ruler [[Baba Ala Singh]] in 1763,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punjabiuniversity.ac.in/pages/forensicseminar/patiala.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118160501/http://www.punjabiuniversity.ac.in/pages/forensicseminar/patiala.htm |archivedate=18 January 2010 }}</ref> who was the founder of the Patiala dynasty. Later, it was reconstructed in baked bricks. The interior portion of Quila, which is known as ''Quila Androon'' is built by [[Maharaja of Patiala|Maharaja Amar Singh]].<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030223/spectrum/patiala.htm The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Lead Article]</ref>\n\n==Quila Mubarak complex==\nThe residential palace of [[Maharaja of Patiala|Royal family of Patiala]], Qila Mubarak complex is built in {{convert|10|acre|m2|adj=on}} ground in the heart of the city. The whole complex contains ''Ran Baas'' ([[Guest house (secondary suite)|Guest house]]) and the ''Darbar Hall'' (Divan Khana)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/TOURISM/Patiala.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728091755/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/tourism/Patiala.htm |archivedate=28 July 2010 }}</ref> besides Quila Androon. There is also underground sewerage system in the Quila.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/TOURISM/PalacesofPunjab.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802204238/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/tourism/PalacesofPunjab.htm |archivedate=2 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Quila Androon===\nQuila Androon has 13 royal chambers with scenes from [[Hindu mythology]] painted in the Patiala art style.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/23525/Simply%20Punjabi/Mighty+edifice.html Mighty edifice : Simply Punjabi - India Today]</ref>\n\n===Museum of Armoury & Chandelier===\nThe Darbar Hall contains rare [[cannon]]s, [[sword]]s, shields and [[Gada (mace)|maces]], [[dagger]]s of [[Guru Gobind Singh]], and sword of [[Nadir Shah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/Culture/Museums.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410202932/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/Culture/Museums.htm |archivedate=10 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Restoration work==\nBeing a 300-year-old building,<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031203/nation.htm#5 The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Nation]</ref> the Quila is described as being in 'bad shape'<ref>[http://www.indiatoday.com/itoday/20031110/heritage.shtml India Today]</ref> and has been extensively damaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmf.org/field/full-project-list |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411210559/http://www.wmf.org/field/full-project-list |archivedate=11 April 2010 }}</ref> The fortress is described by the [[World Monuments Fund]] as one of world\u2019s 100 \"most endangered monuments\" in [[2004 World Monuments Watch List of Most Endangered Sites|year 2004]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nRestoration work of Quila has been undertaken by [[INTACH|Indian National Trust for Arts and Cultural Heritage]], which has been financially assisted by the state and national governments<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040220/punjab1.htm The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Punjab]</ref> [[Archaeological Survey of India]].<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100215/punjab.htm#10 The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Punjab]</ref> The [[World Monuments Watch]] has also funded its preservation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.ukpha.org/2006/03/patiala-fort-to-regain-regal-bearing/ | title=Patiala fort to regain regal bearing | first=Amandeep | last=Madra | date=27 March 2006 | publisher=UK Punjab Heritage Association | accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/patiala-qila-mubarak-rises-former-glory-panorama-punjab-festival/|title=Patiala\u2019s Qila Mubarak rises to former glory with Panorama Punjab festival|date=2018-01-11|website=Architectural Design {{!}} Interior Design {{!}} Home Decoration Magazine {{!}} AD India|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/the-dust-settles-at-qila-mubarak/articleshow/58441790.cms|title=The dust settles at Qila Mubarak - Times of India|last=Sirhindi|first=Manish|date=2017-04-30|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wikimapia.org/446780/Quila-Mubarak @Wikimapia]\n\n{{Forts_in_India}}\n\n{{coord missing|Punjab (India)}}\n\n[[Category:Forts in Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Sikh architecture]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Patiala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Qila Mubarak|Qila Mubarak in Bathinda]]}}\n{{Infobox historic site\n| name = Qila Mubarak\n| native_name = \n| native_language = \n| image = Qila Mubarak, Patiala.jpg\n| caption = \n| type = [[Royal palace]]\n| locmapin = \n| coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} -->\n| location = [[Patiala]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n| area = \n| built = \n| architect = \n| architecture = \n| governing_body = \n| owner = \n| designation1 = \n| designation1_offname = \n| designation1_date = \n| designation1_number = \n| designation2 = \n| designation2_offname = \n| designation2_date = \n| designation2_number = \n| designation3 = \n| designation3_offname = \n| designation3_date = \n| designation3_number = \n| designation4 = \n| designation4_offname = \n| designation4_date = \n| designation4_number = \n| designation5 = \n| designation5_offname = \n| designation5_date = \n| designation5_number = \n}}\n\n'''Qila Mubarak''' ({{Lang-pa|'''\u0a15\u0a3c\u0a3f\u0a32\u0a3e \u0a2e\u0a41\u0a2c\u0a3e\u0a30\u0a15'''}}) is an ancient fortress of [[Sikh architecture]] in [[Patiala]], [[India]].<ref>[http://www.indianexpress.com/oldStory/36639/ 4 heritage sites find saviour in Monument Fund]</ref> \n\n==History==\nQuila Mubarak was first built as a 'Kachigarhi' (Mud fortress) by [[Sidhu]] [[Jat]] ruler [[Baba Ala Singh]] in 1763,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.punjabiuniversity.ac.in/pages/forensicseminar/patiala.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100118160501/http://www.punjabiuniversity.ac.in/pages/forensicseminar/patiala.htm |archivedate=18 January 2010 }}</ref> who was the founder of the Patiala dynasty. Later, it was reconstructed in baked bricks. The interior portion of Quila, which is known as ''Quila Androon'' is built by [[Maharaja of Patiala|Maharaja Amar Singh]].<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20030223/spectrum/patiala.htm The Sunday Tribune - Spectrum - Lead Article]</ref>\n\n==Quila Mubarak complex==\nThe residential palace of [[Maharaja of Patiala|Royal family of Patiala]], Qila Mubarak complex is built in {{convert|10|acre|m2|adj=on}} ground in the heart of the city. The whole complex contains ''Ran Baas'' ([[Guest house (secondary suite)|Guest house]]) and the ''Darbar Hall'' (Divan Khana)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/TOURISM/Patiala.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728091755/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/tourism/Patiala.htm |archivedate=28 July 2010 }}</ref> besides Quila Androon. There is also underground sewerage system in the Quila.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/TOURISM/PalacesofPunjab.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802204238/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/tourism/PalacesofPunjab.htm |archivedate=2 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Quila Androon===\nQuila Androon has 13 royal chambers with scenes from [[Hindu mythology]] painted in the Patiala art style.<ref>[http://indiatoday.intoday.in/site/Story/23525/Simply%20Punjabi/Mighty+edifice.html Mighty edifice : Simply Punjabi - India Today]</ref>\n\n===Museum of Armoury & Chandelier===\nThe Darbar Hall contains rare [[cannon]]s, [[sword]]s, shields and [[Gada (mace)|maces]], [[dagger]]s of [[Guru Gobind Singh]], and sword of [[Nadir Shah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabgovt.nic.in/Culture/Museums.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100410202932/http://punjabgovt.nic.in/Culture/Museums.htm |archivedate=10 April 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Restoration work==\nBeing a 300-year-old building,<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2003/20031203/nation.htm#5 The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Nation]</ref> the Quila is described as being in 'bad shape'<ref>[http://www.indiatoday.com/itoday/20031110/heritage.shtml India Today]</ref> and has been extensively damaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wmf.org/field/full-project-list |title=Archived copy |accessdate=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100411210559/http://www.wmf.org/field/full-project-list |archivedate=11 April 2010 }}</ref> The fortress is described by the [[World Monuments Fund]] as one of world\u2019s 100 \"most endangered monuments\" in [[2004 World Monuments Watch List of Most Endangered Sites|year 2004]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nRestoration work of Quila has been undertaken by [[INTACH|Indian National Trust for Arts and Cultural Heritage]], which has been financially assisted by the state and national governments<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040220/punjab1.htm The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Punjab]</ref> [[Archaeological Survey of India]].<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2010/20100215/punjab.htm#10 The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Punjab]</ref> The [[World Monuments Watch]] has also funded its preservation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.ukpha.org/2006/03/patiala-fort-to-regain-regal-bearing/ | title=Patiala fort to regain regal bearing | first=Amandeep | last=Madra | date=27 March 2006 | publisher=UK Punjab Heritage Association | accessdate=20 March 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architecturaldigest.in/content/patiala-qila-mubarak-rises-former-glory-panorama-punjab-festival/|title=Patiala\u2019s Qila Mubarak rises to former glory with Panorama Punjab festival|date=2018-01-11|website=Architectural Design {{!}} Interior Design {{!}} Home Decoration Magazine {{!}} AD India|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/the-dust-settles-at-qila-mubarak/articleshow/58441790.cms|title=The dust settles at Qila Mubarak - Times of India|last=Sirhindi|first=Manish|date=2017-04-30|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://wikimapia.org/446780/Quila-Mubarak @Wikimapia]\n\n{{Forts_in_India}}\n\n{{coord missing|Punjab (India)}}\n\n[[Category:Forts in Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Sikh architecture]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Patiala]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix links to Punjab (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qila_Mubarak,_Patiala"}
